Description: We investigate how the COVID-19 health crisis could affect the liquidity of Dutch SMEs. We stress-test several liquidity ratios for each firm with full and partial operating flexibility in two simulated distress scenarios corresponding to sector specific drops in sales of 20 to 75 percent. We investigate the time it take for firms to exhaust its cash holdings under mild and adverse scenarios with no or partial operating. At that point, firms would have to resort to the debt market to prevent a liquidity crunch. We study three different fiscal policies, tax deferrals, loan guarantees and a recently proposed initial cash flow injection against a proportionate participation in future gross earnings.

Joint with Maurice Bun (De Nederlandsche Bank and University of Amsterdam).
